I&#x27;m not sure why you think local variable names are mattering here...<p>What&#x27;s happening is that this expresion:<p><pre><code>    const { error, value } = obj;
</code></pre>
where obj is an object will assign obj.error to error and obj.value to value.<p>You could name your locals something else if you wanted, of course:<p><pre><code>    const { error: myError, value: myValue } = obj;
</code></pre>
will assign obj.error to myError and obj.value to myValue.  There just happens to be a shorter syntax for the common<p><pre><code>   const { error: error, value: value } = obj;
</code></pre>
case.
